            created_at: 1455980447,
            text_fragment: {
              id: "2596011",
              plain_text: "Another short hop deposited us in a delightful hilltop village called St. Paul de Vence. The perfect exemplar of a well preserved medieval walled town. Except for modern wares and associated signage, and a few other amenities, it is as if development was arrested 500–600 years ago.\n\nImpossibly narrow passages, stone walls and cobbled streets transport the visitor to another time. A time that is outright illegal in America! More and more, as we visit various sites, I am struck at how delightful they are, and how forbidden these architectural treats are to everyday America— forbidden to us at home by the well–meaning but darkly oppressive overlords of the administrative state who have decided to take care of us and prevent all manner of imagined and real harms—at the expense of variety, wonder, and imagination. It is abundantly clear, in contrast with this environment, that it is not worth the price. \n\nThe problem for urban planners everywhere is denialism of the unpredictable (and therefore un–plan–able) wonders of emergent order. The best environments aren't planned, they emerge from the myriad decisions of individuals. Medieval and Renaissance Europe is a testament to this reality so central to human nature. It is too bad that we deny its full flower in our country (I also blame the lobbyists, lawyers and the unscrupulous greed and morals of those that hire them to extract unearned wealth or to impose their will on others—we're looking at you, corporatists, environmentalists and so–called social justice warriors).",
              text_style: "body",
              modifiers: [{ range: [407, 414], style: ["bold", "italic"] }],
              alignment: "left"
            },
